{"title_page": "Mary Scott (missionary)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Mary Hepburn Scott\n| image = \n| caption =  \n| birth_date = 1887\n| nationality = Scottish\n| fields = Medical Missionary\n| workplaces = Sikkim\n| known_for = Medical service and Girls' Education\n}}\n\n'''Mary Hepburn Scott''' (1887 \u2013 ''after'' 1938) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] Missionary and Educator who pioneered women's education in [[Sikkim]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://lib.icimod.org/record/11595/files/6671.pdf?version=1|title=The indigenization of Western Medicine in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=lib.icimod.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Despite her lack of formal medical training, she became the leading medical, educational and religious missionary in [[Gangtok]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/149360/11/11_chapter_03.pdf|title=Women's Education Over Time in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=lib.icimod.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> educating an entire generation of Sikkimese physicians and significantly improving health outcomes,<ref name=\":02\"/> despite Christian missionaries historically not being allowed in Gangtok for political and religious reasons.<ref name=\":2\" />  Scott also founded Gangtok's first girls school,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/149360/11/11_chapter_03.pdf|title=Society, Women and Education in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> the [[Paljor Namgyal Girls' School]], which still exists today and has been credited with greatly improving the overall state of women's education in Sikkim both historically and currently.<ref name=\":1\" /> Additionally, Scott has been recognized for almost-single-handedly creating the largest period of growth in Christianity in Sikkim, which still significantly impacts Sikkim's religious demographics.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":32\"/>\n\n== Early life and Kalimpong ==\nMary Scott was born in 1877 to the 8th [[Lord Polwarth]].<ref name=\":02\"/> Little is known of her aristocratic upbringing, other than that she received no formal medical education.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=http://lib.icimod.org/record/11595/files/6671.pdf?version=1|title=History Culture and Customs of Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1905, she travelled to [[Kalimpong]] to work as a Christian missionary<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eo5QDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT39&lpg=PT39&dq=Mary+Scott+kalimpong#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Scott%20kalimpong&f=false|title=Facing Mount Kanchenjunga|last=Sangharakshita|date=2014-04-29|publisher=Windhorse Publications|isbn=9781909314382|language=en}}</ref> with the [[Church of Scotland]] mission.<ref name=\":02\" /> Despite her lack of formal medical education, she was one of the first women to win the [[Kaisar-i-Hind Medal]] for her work during the [[Spanish flu]] epidemic of 1918\u20131919.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was also awarded an honorary degree in theology from a Scottish university for her relative success in converting the [[Lepcha people]] of Sikkim to Christianity despite the failure of numerous earlier attempts at conversion.,<ref name=\":32\" /> despite her lack of medical training, she acquired a reputation for good works and reliability, and for serving the general population of Sikkim as well as its Christian population.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/149360/11/11_chapter_03.pdf|title=Society, Women and Education in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Scott was also considered a highly competent administrator, and proved highly adept at navigating Gangtok's politics despite the heavy suspicion she attracted due to her religion, aristocratic background and gender.<ref name=\":22\" />  Despite receiving substantial state support and repeatedly being offered a salary, Scott refused any personal payment and supported herself by selling paintings she made in her spare time.<ref name=\":6\" /> Scott also acquired a reputation for humility, refusing to write letters to Scotland because she feared it would make herself appear less part of the community, especially in light of her aristocratic background and her status as a religious missionary.<ref name=\":6\" /> After retiring as the official missionary of Sikkim in 1939, White returned to Kalimpong and founded a school for the blind in 1940,<ref name=\":6\" /> which still bears her name. In the 1990s, the Mary Scott School for the Blind in Kalimpong revolutionized blind education in Southeast India by being the first to introduce Brail technology.<ref name=\":6\" /> The school is still in existence with over 60 students as of 2014, and has entered into a partnership with the [[Salvation Army|salvation army]] to expand.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newfrontierchronicle.org/education-for-life/|title=Education for life|last=|first=|date=2014-12-28|website=New Frontier Chronicle|language=en-US|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== PNG School ==\nIn 1923 Scott succeeded the previous missionary of Sikkim Reverend Maclean, and moved to the Sikkimese capital of Gangtok. This marked a major concession by the raj of Sikkim, because previously Christian missionaries had been forbidden from living in Gangtok.<ref name=\":2\" /> Explanations given for the special privilege given to White include her aristocratic background, her prior reputation and aid in the epidemic, and her strong relations with the Sikkimese elite, which largely arose from her reputation for efficient work and tolerating Budhist customs when fighting epidemics.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\":5\" /> She established Palmor Namzygar Girls School ([http://www.pngschool.edu.in/ PNG School]) in 1924.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lNAmQOIpH4EC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=Mary+scott+gangtok#v=onepage&q=Mary%20scott%20gangtok&f=false|title=Sikkim Development Report|last=Commission|first=India Planning|date=2008|publisher=Academic Foundation|isbn=9788171886685|language=en}}</ref> The school began with just two pupils who Scott recruited by asking door-to-door.<ref name=\":2\" /> With assistance from the Sikkim State government and the Catholic church<ref name=\":2\" /> she gradually grew the school into a fully fledged secondary school that was recognized by [[University of Calcutta]] in 1945<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://14.139.206.50:8080/jspui/bitstream/1/6082/1/2018_08_29_16_23_33.pdf|title=Women Education and Mary Scott in Sikim|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and formally accredited by the [[government of India]] in 1961.<ref name=\":2\" /> The PNG was known for focusing on practical skills that would help Sikkim develop rather than learning-for-learning's sake,<ref name=\":2\" /> and eventually established a complete special program in knitting despite a near complete lack of familiarity when she arrived.<ref name=\":42\"/> While initially founded as the first Gangtok school for girls the PNG school eventually accepted boys as well.<ref name=\":1\" /> Due to difficulty acquiring staff, Scott convinced the local government to fund sending graduates of the school elsewhere for education, after which they would return to Gangtok as teachers.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Medical missionary ==\n[[File:Tashi Namgyal.jpg|thumb|[[Tashi Namgyal]], the ruler or [[Chogyal]] of Sikkim, who allowed White to relocate to Sikkim and strongly supported her medical-missionary activities.]]\n\nFrom her earlier days in Gangtok, Scott used her position in Gangtok to begin a successful medical mission.<ref name=\":02\"/> While Gangtok had little medical infrastructure and the prior missionary of Sikkim Reverend Maclean had not given any attention to medical work, he had recommended that his successor be a medical missionary.<ref name=\":02\"/> Despite her lack of formal medical training, White devoted much of her efforts to medical efforts, at times caring for the sick inside her own home during the [[Visceral leishmaniasis]] epidemics.<ref name=\":32\"/> From the beginning, Scott ensured that the medical mission was primarily run by Sikkimese workers, which was unusual for medical Missions at the time, and helped accelerate the creation of a class of Western trained doctors and pharmacists in Sikim.<ref name=\":02\"/> While none of Scott's students moved beyond compounder status before Scott left in 1939 due to health issues from the altitude, several of her later students would go on to become allopathic medical professionals after her departure, with many of the students receiving substantial financial support from the state government due to Scott's prior actions convincing the Sikkimese elite of the value of medical education<ref name=\":02\"/> Her creation of a class of Western-trained doctors is considered a major reason medicine in Sikkim was not significantly affected by the [[Partition of India]],<ref name=\":02\"/> and Sikkim's success at converting a medical system based on foreign support into a fully functioning indigenous one has been cited as a positive example compared to other regions of modern-day India.<ref name=\":02\"/> Some of her students continued as doctors in Sikkim as late as 1995.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Christian missionary ==\nFrom the beginning of her time as a missionary, Scott worked to balance her educational and medical goals with her role as a Scottish religious missionary.<ref name=\":1\" /> In her medical work in Kalimpong, Scott was known for being tolerant of non-Christians working and receiving education, and saw value in the Buddhist teachings of hard work and responsibility that aligned with her Presbyterian belief's.<ref name=\":32\"/>  The success of Scott's educational efforts led to her receiving permission to open a Christian church in Gangtok in 1936, a strong testament to White's reputation  given the strong opposition to Christian activities by the Chogyal and other political elites in Sikkim.<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite web|url=http://14.139.206.50:8080/jspui/bitstream/1/6082/1/2018_08_29_16_23_33.pdf|title=Women Education and Mary Scott in Sikim|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Scott's reputation as a friend to the general population of Sikkim rather than solely the small but growing Christian minority is considered a major reason for the unique privileges she was given compared to prior and subsequent missionaries.<ref name=\":6\" /> While Scott's  successor as Scottish Mission in Gangtok, the Reverend Gavin Fairservice,  continued White's missionary efforts, he was not allowed to reside in Sikkim and his evangelizing was strictly monitored by the local government.<ref name=\":02\"/> The ''Presbyterian Missionary Church'' Scott founded with the Chogyal's special permission is still in existence today,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deviantart.com/palzephyr/art/Presbyterian-Church-214870284|title=Presbyteryan Church Gangtok|last=|first=|date=|website=deviantart.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the Presbyterian Missionary Church remains the largest Christian denomination in Sikkim, with the majority of its adherents being the descendants of those converted by Scott and other missionaries in the late nineteenth and early 20th centuries.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://irfa.org.au/about/a-portrait-of-india/|title=A Portrait of India {{!}}|website=irfa.org.au|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref> Given the strong growth of Christianity during Scott's period as missionary, her efforts are considered a primary reason Christians are a significant minority in Sikkim today.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Mary}}\n[[Category:Scottish missionaries]]\n[[Category:Female Christian missionaries]]\n[[Category:Medical missionaries]]\n[[Category:Sikhism]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Mary Hepburn Scott\n| image = \n| caption =  \n| birth_date = 1887\n| nationality = Scottish\n| fields = Medical Missionary\n| workplaces = Sikkim\n| known_for = Medical service and Girls' Education\n}}\n\n'''Mary Hepburn Scott''' (born 1887) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] Missionary and Educator who pioneered women's education in [[Sikkim]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://lib.icimod.org/record/11595/files/6671.pdf?version=1|title=The indigenization of Western Medicine in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=lib.icimod.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Despite her lack of formal medical training, she became the leading medical, educational and religious missionary in [[Gangtok]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/149360/11/11_chapter_03.pdf|title=Women's Education Over Time in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=lib.icimod.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> educating an entire generation of Sikkimese physicians and significantly improving health outcomes,<ref name=\":02\"/> despite Christian missionaries historically not being allowed in Gangtok for political and religious reasons.<ref name=\":2\" />  Scott also founded Gangtok's first girls school,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/149360/11/11_chapter_03.pdf|title=Society, Women and Education in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> the [[Paljor Namgyal Girls' School]], which still exists today and has been credited with greatly improving the overall state of women's education in Sikkim both historically and currently.<ref name=\":1\" /> Additionally, Scott has been recognized for almost-single-handedly creating the largest period of growth in Christianity in Sikkim, which still significantly impacts Sikkim's religious demographics.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":32\"/>\n\n== Early Life and Kalimpong ==\nMary Scott was born in 1877 to the 8th [[Lord Polwarth]].<ref name=\":02\"/> Little is known of her aristocratic upbringing, other than that she received no formal medical education.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=http://lib.icimod.org/record/11595/files/6671.pdf?version=1|title=History Culture and Customs of Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1905, she travelled to [[kalimpong]] to work as a Christian missionary<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eo5QDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT39&lpg=PT39&dq=Mary+Scott+kalimpong#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Scott%20kalimpong&f=false|title=Facing Mount Kanchenjunga|last=Sangharakshita|date=2014-04-29|publisher=Windhorse Publications|isbn=9781909314382|language=en}}</ref> with the [[Church of Scotland]] mission.<ref name=\":02\" /> Despite her lack of formal medical education, she was one of the first women to win the [[Kaisar-i-Hind Medal]] for her work during the [[Spanish flu]] epidemic of 1918-1919.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was also awarded an honorary degree in theology from a Scottish university for her relative success in converting the [[Lepcha people]] of Sikkim to Christianity despite the failure of numerous earlier attempts at conversion.,<ref name=\":32\" /> despite her lack of medical training, she acquired a reputation for good works and reliability, and for serving the general population of Sikkim as well as it's Christian population.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/149360/11/11_chapter_03.pdf|title=Society, Women and Education in Sikkim|last=|first=|date=|website=shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Scott was also considered a highly competent administrator, and proved highly adept at navigating Gangtok's politics despite the heavy suspicion she attracted due to her religion, aristocratic background and gender.<ref name=\":22\" />  Despite receiving substantial state support and repeatedly being offered a salary, Scott refused any personal payment and supported herself by selling paintings she made in her spare time, .<ref name=\":6\" /> Scott also acquired a reputation for humility, refusing to write letters to Scotland because she feared it would make herself appear less part of the community, especially in light of her aristocratic background and her status as a religious missionary.<ref name=\":6\" /> After retiring as the official missionary of Sikkim in 1939, White returned to Kalimpong and founded a school for the blind in 1940,<ref name=\":6\" /> which still bears her name. In the 1990s, the Mary Scott School for the Blind in Kalimpong revolutionized blind education in Southeast India by being the first to introduce Brail technology.<ref name=\":6\" /> The school is still in existence with over 60 students as of 2014, and has entered into a partnership with the [[Salvation Army|salvation army]] to expand.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newfrontierchronicle.org/education-for-life/|title=Education for life|last=|first=|date=2014-12-28|website=New Frontier Chronicle|language=en-US|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== PNG School ==\nIn 1923 Scott succeeded the previous missionary of Sikkim Reverend Maclean, and moved to the Sikkimese capital of Gangtok. This marked a major concession by the raj of Sikkim, because previously Christian missionaries had been forbidden from living in Gangtok.<ref name=\":2\" /> Explanations given for the special privilege given to White include her aristocratic background, her prior reputation and aid in the epidemic, and her strong relations with the Sikkimese elite, which largely arose from her reputation for efficient work and tolerating Budhist customs when fighting epidemics.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\":5\" /> She established Palmor Namzygar Girls School ([http://www.pngschool.edu.in/ PNG School]) in 1924.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lNAmQOIpH4EC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=Mary+scott+gangtok#v=onepage&q=Mary%20scott%20gangtok&f=false|title=Sikkim Development Report|last=Commission|first=India Planning|date=2008|publisher=Academic Foundation|isbn=9788171886685|language=en}}</ref> The school began with just two pupils who Scott recruited by asking door-to-door.<ref name=\":2\" /> With assistance from the Sikkim State government and the Catholic church<ref name=\":2\" /> she gradually grew the school into a fully fledged secondary school that was recognized by [[University of Calcutta|Calcutta university]] in 1945<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://14.139.206.50:8080/jspui/bitstream/1/6082/1/2018_08_29_16_23_33.pdf|title=Women Education and Mary Scott in Sikim|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and formally accredited by the [[government of India]] in 1961.<ref name=\":2\" /> The PNG  was known for focusing on practical skills that would help Sikkim develop rather than learning-for-learning's sake,<ref name=\":2\" /> and eventually established a complete special program in knitting despite a near complete lack of familiarity when she arrived.<ref name=\":42\"/> While initially founded as the first Gangtok school for girls the PNG school eventually accepted boys as well.<ref name=\":1\" /> Due to difficulty acquiring staff, Scott convinced the local government to fund sending graduates of the school elsewhere for education, after which they would return to Gangtok as teachers.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Medical Missionary ==\n[[File:Tashi Namgyal.jpg|thumb|[[Tashi Namgyal]], the ruler or [[Chogyal]] of Sikkim, who allowed White to relocate to Sikkim and strongly supported her medical-missionary activities.]]\n\nFrom her earlier days in Gangtok, Scott used her position in Gangtok to begin a successful medical mission.<ref name=\":02\"/> While Gangtok had little medical infrastructure and the prior missionary of Sikkim Reverend Maclean had not given any attention to medical work, he had recommended that his successor be a medical missionary.<ref name=\":02\"/> Despite her lack of formal medical training, White devoted much of her efforts to medical efforts, at times caring for the sick inside her own home during the [[Visceral leishmaniasis]] epidemics.<ref name=\":32\"/> From the beginning, Scott ensured that the medical mission was primarily run by Sikkimese workers, which was unusual for medical Missions at the time, and helped accelerate the creation of a class of Western trained doctors and pharmacists in Sikim.<ref name=\":02\"/> While none of Scott's students moved beyond compounder status before Scott left in 1939 due to health issues from the altitude, several of her later students would go on to become allopathic medical professionals after her departure, with many of the students receiving substantial financial support from the state government due to Scott's prior actions convincing the Sikkimese elite of the value of medical education<ref name=\":02\"/> Her creation of a class of Western-trained doctors is considered a major reason medicine in Sikkim was not significantly affected by the [[Partition of India]],<ref name=\":02\"/> and Sikkim's success at converting a medical system based on foreign support into a fully functioning indigenous one has been cited as a positive example compared to other regions of modern-day India.<ref name=\":02\"/> Some of her students continued as doctors in Sikkim as late as 1995.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== Christian Missionary ==\nFrom the beginning of her time as a missionary, Scott worked to balance her educational and medical goals with her role as a Scottish religious missionary.<ref name=\":1\" /> In her medical work in Kalimpong, Scott was known for being tolerant of non-Christians working and receiving education, and saw value in the Buddhist teachings of hard work and responsibility that aligned with her Presbyterian belief's.<ref name=\":32\"/>  The success of Scott's educational efforts led to her receiving permission to open a Christian church in Gangtok in 1936, a strong testament to White's reputation  given the strong opposition to Christian activities by the Chogyal and other political elites in Sikkim.<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite web|url=http://14.139.206.50:8080/jspui/bitstream/1/6082/1/2018_08_29_16_23_33.pdf|title=Women Education and Mary Scott in Sikim|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Scott's reputation as a friend to the general population of Sikkim rather than solely the small but growing Christian minority is considered a major reason for the unique privileges she was given compared to prior and subsequent missionaries.<ref name=\":6\" /> While Scott's  successor as Scottish Mission in Gangtok, the Reverend Gavin Fairservice,  continued White's missionary efforts, he was not allowed to reside in Sikkim and his evangelizing was strictly monitored by the local government.<ref name=\":02\"/> The ''Presbyterian Missionary Church'' Scott founded with the Chogyal's special permission is still in existence today,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deviantart.com/palzephyr/art/Presbyterian-Church-214870284|title=Presbyteryan Church Gangtok|last=|first=|date=|website=deviantart.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the Presbyterian Missionary Church remains the largest Christian denomination in Sikkim, with the majority of its adherents being the descendants of those converted by Scott and other missionaries in the late nineteenth and early 20th centuries.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://irfa.org.au/about/a-portrait-of-india/|title=A Portrait of India {{!}}|website=irfa.org.au|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref> Given the strong growth of Christianity during Scott's period as missionary, her efforts are considered a primary reason Christians are a significant minority in Sikkim today.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Mary}}\n[[Category:Scottish missionaries]]\n[[Category:Female Christian missionaries]]\n[[Category:Medical missionaries]]\n[[Category:Sikhism]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death uncertain]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Scott_(missionary)"}
