ck At Postal Annex Costing Millions | website=The New York Times | date=1979-04-09 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/04/09/archives/an-empty-block-at-postal-annex-costing-millions-residents-of.html | ref={{sfnref|Empty Block At Postal Annex|1979}}| access-date=2017-11-01}}\n*{{cite news | ref={{harvid|BOARD ABANDONS PLAN 1938}}\n |title=BOARD ABANDONS PLAN FOR SCHOOL IN PARK; Protests Against Building in Chelsea Area Result in Dropping of Project | work=The New York Times | date=1938-02-02\n |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1938/02/02/96792987.pdf | access-date=2017-10-31}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\n |title=Chelsea Park|publisher=NYC Parks\n |url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/chelsea-park|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}}\n |title=Chelsea Park Memorial (Doughboy)|publisher=NYC Parks\n |url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/chelsea-park/monuments/232|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{Cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Tribune%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Tribune%25201907%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Tribune%25201907%252007-23%2520Page%25208.pdf\n |title=CHELSEA PARK DELAYED|last=|first=|date=July 23, 1907|work=New York Daily Tribune|access-date=October 30, 2017|page=8|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]|ref={{harvid|CHELSEA PARK DELAYED}}}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1953/11/11/84074876.pdf\n |title=Chelsea Park Enlarged|last=|first=|date=November 11, 1953|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2017\n |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|Chelsea Park Enlarged 1953}} }}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/09/10/118948209.pdf\n |title=CHELSEA PARK OPPOSED.; Middle West Sider Argues for Block Further North.|last=|first=|date=September 10, 1904|work=The New York Times\n |access-date=October 30, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|CHELSEA PARK OPPOSED 1904}}}}\n*{{citation |title=Chelsea Park \u2013 New York NY\n |last=Cruz|first=Frank da  |date=October 6, 2016|work=Living New Deal\n |url=https://livingnewdeal.org/projects/chelsea-park-new-york-ny/|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{citation\n |author=Edwards and Kelcey|title=Manhattan Postal Station Vehicle Maintenance Facility: Environmental Impact Statement\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X9w3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA21|accessdate=October 30, 2017|year=1977}}\n*{{citation\n |author=Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|title=Manhattan General Mail Facility: Environmental Impact Statement\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ot03AQAAMAAJ&pg=PT36|volume=Volume 1|accessdate=October 30, 2017|year=1989|ref={{sfnref|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a}}}}\n*{{citation\n |author=Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|title=Manhattan General Mail Facility: Environmental Impact Statement\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YN03AQAAMAAJ|volume=Volume 2: Appendix|accessdate=October 30, 2017|year=1989|ref={{sfnref|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989b}}}}\n*{{citation\n |last=Fitzpatrick|first=Kevin C.|title=World War I New York: A Guide to the City's Enduring Ties to The Great War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=esctDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT73 \n |accessdate=October 30, 2017|date=April 20, 2017|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|isbn=978-1-4930-2804-7}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Frank L. Dowling ... Culture Now}} |title=Frank L. Dowling, William L. Kavanagh, Frank J. Goodwin, 1926 |work=Culture Now \n |url=http://culturenow.org/entry&permalink=03369&seo=Frank-L-Dowling-William-L-Kavanagh-Frank-J-Goodwin_Murry-and-Matheson-and-Unknown|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{citation|title=Windows and Vegetation: Primary Factors in Manhattan Bird Collisions\n |last1=Gelb |last2=Delacretaz|first1=Yigal |first2=Nicole|journal=Northeastern Naturalist|volume=16|issue=3 |year=2009\n |publisher=Eagle Hill Institute|jstor=27744581}}\n* {{cite news |ref={{harvid|GIVES TWO GATES TO CITY 1926}}\n | title=GIVES TWO GATES TO CITY.; Third District Tammany Club Unveils Portals in Chelsea Park. | work=The New York Times | date=October 18, 1926\n | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1926/10/18/98398922.pdf | access-date=October 30, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}\n*{{Cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Daily%2520Worker%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Daily%2520Worker%25201937%2520Jun-Oct%25201937%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Daily%2520Worker%25201937%2520Jun-Oct%25201937%252000098.pdf\n |title=Health Center On West Side To Be Opened |last=|first=|date=July 12, 1937|work=New York Daily Worker|access-date=October 30, 2017|page=5|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]] |ref={{harvid|Health Center On West Side To Be Opened}}}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1935/08/09/93692816.pdf\n |title=Health Centre to Cost $175,000 |last=|first=|date=August 9, 1935|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 31, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|Health Centre to Cost $175,000}}}}\n*{{cite news |ref={{harvid|MAYOR BARS PRAISE FOR HEALTH CENTER}} \n |title=MAYOR BARS PRAISE FOR HEALTH CENTER; Shifts Credit to Roosevelt at Dedication of Building in Chelsea Park | work=The New York Times | date=1937-07-14 \n |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1937/07/14/94400447.pdf| access-date=2017-10-31}}\n*{{cite news |ref={{harvid|MAYOR REDEDICATES CHELSEA PLAYGROUND}}\n |title=MAYOR REDEDICATES CHELSEA PLAYGROUND; Neighborhood Is Decorated as Reconstructed Park Opens. | work=The New York Times | date=1940-06-07\n |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/06/07/93982089.pdf | access-date=2017-10-31}}\n* {{cite news | title=NEW PLAY CENTER UP TO BOARD TODAY; Bronx Project Is First of Eight Planned for Four Boroughs in $7,600,000 Program REST TO WAIT FOR FUNDS Developments Will Provide Year-Round Recreation for Congested Districts | work=The New York Times | date=1949-07-21 | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1949/07/21/84574055.pdf | ref={{sfnref |NEW PLAY CENTER| 1949}} | access-date=2017-10-31}}\n*{{citation|title=Expanded Moynihan/Penn Station Redevelopment Project - Comments on the Draft Scope of Work for the Supplemental Environmental Impact Statement\n |last1=Noland |last2=Levin |last3=Compton |last4=Kotler |first1=Jean-Daniel |first2=Anna Hayes |first3=J. Lee|first4=Lynn|date=December 14, 2007 |publisher=City of New York \n |url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/mancb4/downloads/pdf/agendas/2007_12/17_chklu_moynihan_expansion_scope_comments.pdf|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last=Oser | first=Alan S. | title=Perspectives: Land Use; Postal Trucks Find a Home on 11th Ave. | work=The New York Times | date=1988-09-18 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/09/18/realestate/perspectives-land-use-postal-trucks-find-a-home-on-11th-ave.html | ref={{sfnref|Postal Trucks Find a Home|1988}} | access-date=2017-11-01}}\n* {{citation|ref={{harvid|P.O. David Willis Basketball Court}}\n |title=P.O. David Willis Basketball Court|publisher=NYC Parks\n |url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/chelsea-park/highlights/6467|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n* {{cite news |title=Postal Annex Swept By Fire, 1,800 Flee; 1,800 Evacuated as Blaze Sweeps a Major Postal Station on the West Side|work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/12/16/90908608.pdf|date=December 18, 1967|accessdate=October 30, 2017|ref={{harvid|Postal Annex Swept By Fire|1967}}}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1935/08/09/93692816.pdf\n |title=Health Centre to Cost $175,000 |last=|first=|date=August 9, 1935|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 31, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|Health Centre to Cost $175,000}}}}\n*{{citation |title=Chelsea Park Handball Courts Reopen After Renovation |last=Rajamani |first=Maya |date=August 23, 2016 |publisher=DNAinfo |url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20160823/chelsea/chelsea-park-handball-courts-reopen-after-renovation |accessdate=October 30, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107010424/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20160823/chelsea/chelsea-park-handball-courts-reopen-after-renovation |archivedate=November 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}\n*{{citation |title=Lipid Content of Nearctic-Neotropical Migratory Passerines Killed during Stopovers in a New York City Park\n |last=Seewagen|first=Chad L.|journal=Northeastern Naturalist|volume=15|issue=1 |year=2008\n |publisher=Eagle Hill Institute|jstor=25177085}}\n*{{cite news | title=TANK CRASH CAUSES CHELSEA PARK PANIC; Two Boys Badly Hurt -- Water Drenches Scores of Women and Children Near By. 20,000 GALLONS IN FLOOD Mothers Missing Youngsters Are in Hysteria at Hearing Roar of Collapse. CRIMINAL INQUIRY STARTED Tank Was Attached by Girders to Brick of Old Eighth Regiment Armory Building. | work=The New York Times | date=1925-08-18 | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1925/08/18/101675586.pdf | ref={{harvid|TANK CRASH CAUSES CHELSEA PARK PANIC}} | access-date=2017-10-31}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1906/06/30/101376701.pdf\n |title=To Hasten Chelsea Park|last=|first=|date=June 30, 1906|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|To Hasten Chelsea Park}}}}\n*{{citation|title=Over the Top: The Doughboy in World War I Memorials and Visual Culture\n |last=Wingate|first=Jennifer |journal=American Art|volume=19|issue=2 |date=Summer 2005 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press on behalf of the Smithsonian American Art Museum\n |doi=10.1086/444480 |jstor=10.1086/444480 |pages=26\u201347}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Protected areas of New York City}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chelsea Park}}\n[[Category:Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Parks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:1910 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the park in Sheffield|Chelsea Park (Sheffield)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name           = Chelsea Park\n| image          = Chelsea Park (6007936871).jpg\n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| image_caption  = Artificial turf soccer field\n| map            = Manhattan#New York City\n| map_width      = \n| type           = Urban park \n| location       = Bounded by Ninth & Tenth Avenues and West 27th & 28th Streets\n| nearest_city   = [[New York City]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|40.750030|-74.000923|display=it}}\n| area           = \n| created        = 1910\n| operator       = [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]\n| visitation_num = \n| status         = \n| designation    = \n| open           = \n}}\n'''Chelsea Park''' is a park on the west side of the [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], United States, that dates back to 1910. \nThe park has sports fields, basketball and handball courts, a children's playground and  space for sitting. The surface is mostly tarmac or artificial turf, with pits for the plane trees and some plots with annual flower plantings. There is a statue to a World War I soldier, the \"Doughboy Statue\", erected in 1921. The process of approval, funding and clearing the tenements that occupied the site was protracted. The park has since been upgraded several times by the [[Works Progress Administration]] and the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]].\n\n==Location==\n\nChelsea Park is located between [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth]] and [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth]] Avenues, and between West 27th and West 28th Streets in Manhattan.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\nThe park covers almost {{convert|4|acre}}.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-230}}\nThere is fencing around the park to contain the active play areas, with gates at various points. The soccer pitch is surrounded by taller fencing while the rest of the park is surrounded by shorter fences.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-230}}\n\nThe area between West 26th and West 28th Streets and 9th and 10th Avenues is a [[City block#Superblock|superblock]], comprising two normal-sized blocks.\nWest 27th Drive is a driveway used only for service access, with the park occupying most of the block to the north of the drive.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-228}}\nTo the south along 26th Street are three 12-to-14-story brick towers run by the [[New York City Housing Authority]] in the southern part of the superblock, as well as a public school (PS&nbsp;33 Chelsea Prep) and the Hudson Guild Settlement House.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989b|pp=\u25a1-106 to \u25a1-107}}{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-228}}\nThe annex to the [[Morgan General Mail Facility]] occupies the block directly to the north of the park.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-229}}\nThe [[Church of the Holy Apostles (Manhattan)|Church of the Holy Apostles]], built in 1848, is located on the east side of 9th Avenue across from the park. It is located within the [[Penn South]] housing complex.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-229}}\n\n==Physical==\n===Infrastructure===\nChelsea Park has spaces for both passive and active recreation.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-230}}\nIt is one of the busier parks in the neighborhood.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\nIt contains baseball diamonds, basketball courts and six handball courts.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\nThe artificial turf sports field covers about one third of the area.{{sfn|Seewagen|2008|p=87}}\nThe P.O. David Willis Basketball Court is named after the [[New York City Police Department]] officer David Willis (1964\u201395), who used to patrol the park.{{sfn|P.O. David Willis Basketball Court}}\nThere are public washrooms at West 27th Street and 9th Avenue, open year-round.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\nThe park contains a District Health Center, a low-rise red brick building in the eastern part of the park.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-228}}\n\n===Ecology===\nThere are no artificial or natural ponds.\nAs of 2008 there were 27 mature London plane trees (''[[Platanus \u00d7 acerifolia]]'') with heights of {{convert|15|to|20|m}} around the perimeter of the park, and another 28 similar trees scattered through the interior.\nMost of the trees are in pits, because most of the ground surface is impermeable.\nThe beds of annual plants around the monument and the health center are the only vegetated and permeable areas of the park other than the tree pits.{{sfn|Seewagen|2008|p=87}}\nThe northwest section of the park has less vegetation than the southeast section.{{sfn|Gelb|Delacretaz|2009|p=459}}\n\nThe six-story Morgan Mail Building along the northern perimeter is a high-collision site for birds, with collisions peaking in mid May.{{sfn|Gelb|Delacretaz|2009|p=460}}\nThe first two stories of the building have featureless concrete walls, while the upper four stories are 75% covered with reflective glass panels installed over the concrete wall to give the appearance of windows.{{sfn|Gelb|Delacretaz|2009|p=461}}\nA study in the spring and autumn of 2005 and 2006 collected the corpses of many migratory birds that had collided with the windows of the six-story USPS building, deceived by the reflections of the greenery in the park.{{sfn|Seewagen|2008|p=87}}\nIt seemed that the birds generally had adequate stores of fat (energy), and it was not clear whether they were stopping in Chelsea Park to replenish their energy or as a reaction to the inhospitable and unfamiliar city landscape.{{sfn|Seewagen|2008|p=93}}\nAbout 80% of collisions are fatal, with most collisions occurring during the day.{{sfn|Gelb|Delacretaz|2009|p=462}}\nMost are found along the southeast perimeter, where there are most trees, while relatively few are found along the playing field perimeter.\nThis suggests that the reflections of trees in the glass panels are a major factor.{{sfn|Gelb|Delacretaz|2009|p=463}}\n\n=== Doughboy Statue ===\n[[File:Chelsea Park sketch map.svg|thumb|Sketch map. BB: Baseball diamond; HB: Handball; BSK: Basketball; GP: Gateposts; MO: Monument]]\nThe park is one of nine New York City parks with monuments to local heroes of [[World War I]] (1914\u201318).\nThe Chelsea Park Memorial, also known as the Doughboy Statue, is a granite stele {{convert|14|ft}} tall fronted by a plinth supporting a bronze statue of an American soldier.{{sfn|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}}\n(\"[[Doughboy]]\" is a slang term for an infantryman that was widely used in World War I.{{sfn|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}})\nThe plinth bears the inscription: \"To the Soldiers and Sailors of Chelsea World War 1914\u20131918\".{{sfn|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}}\nThe monument is surrounded by cobblestone.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-228}}\nIt stands in front of the more recently built Health Center.{{sfn|Fitzpatrick|2017|p=73}}\n\nThe memorial was designed by the architect [[Charles Rollinson Lamb]] (1860\u20131942).\nThe statue was created by the French-born sculptor [[Philip Martiny]] (1858\u20131927) and cast by the Roman Bronze Works foundry of New York.{{sfn|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}}\nThe soldier holds a rifle and has a flag draped over his shoulders.{{sfn|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}}\nHe strikes a commanding pose, defying the enemy.{{sfn|Wingate|2005|p=38}}\nThe city's Art Commission, chaired by sculptor [[Robert Ingersoll Aitken|Robert Aitken]], rejected Martiny's first submission in which the doughboy's pose was less dynamic.{{sfn|Wingate|2005|p=47}}\nMartiny used the same model for the doughboy as he did for his next statue of a soldier, in [[Greenwich Village]].\nThe soldier's aggressive pose is exactly the same as in Martiny's poster for the propaganda film ''Under Four Flags'' (1918).{{sfn|Fitzpatrick|2017|p=73}}\n\n=== Gateposts ===\nAlso in front of the  District Health Center there are two memorial gate posts that were commissioned by the Horatio Seymour Tammany Club and installed in 1926.{{sfn|GIVES TWO GATES TO CITY 1926}}\nThey commemorate the former borough president Frank L Dowling, the municipal civic court leader Frank J. Goodwin and the New York State Democratic Committee member William L. Kavanagh.{{sfn|Frank L. Dowling ... Culture Now}}\n\n==History==\n===Early years (1904\u201318)===\nThe Chelsea Improvement Society proposed a playground for the park's current location in 1904 due to the paucity of parks along Ninth Avenue, with no parks on the street between [[DeWitt Clinton Park]] at 53rd Street and [[St. John's Park|Hudson Park]] at Varick Street.{{sfn|A CHELSEA PLAYGROUND 1904}}\nAt the time, P.S. 33 occupied an adjacent lot.{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1908|p=150}}\nLand had been set aside for a proposed [[Carnegie library]] to the east.{{sfn|A CHELSEA PLAYGROUND 1904}}\nThe rest of the area was full of [[tenement]]s.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1908|p=150}}\nOne reader wrote to ''[[The New York Times]]'' opposing the park and advocating another park site further north that would be located near a greater number of people.{{sfn|CHELSEA PARK OPPOSED 1904}}\nAnother reader proposed a larger park.{{sfn|A WEST SIDE PARK 1904}}\nThe legislature passed bills authorizing the park twice, but both times the mayor vetoed the bills as an \"infringement of home rule\".{{sfn|$4,000,000 VOTED FOR PARKS}}\n$2.23 million was set aside to acquire the park in summer 1905.{{sfn|To Hasten Chelsea Park}}\n\nThe city's parks department finally acquired the titles for all the required properties in 1906.{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1906|p=22}}\nAt the time, the acquisition comprised approximately {{Convert|3.177|acre|ha}}.{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1906|p=76}}\nDemolitions continued at a slow pace: by July 1907, only two cellars had been cleared.{{sfn|CHELSEA PARK DELAYED}}\nFilling started on the excavated properties by the end of that year.{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1907|p=56}} \nA temporary playground was built in 1908.{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1908|p=72}}\nThe first permanent playground in the park was opened in June 1910.{{sfn|NYC Parks Annual Report|1910|pp=26\u201327}}\nBy that time, a baseball field was planned for the park.{{sfn|ALL BARE PLOTS|1910}}\nThe [[New York City Board of Recreation]], which had recently been formed, began to arrange sporting events that drew crowds of spectators.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\n\n===Interwar period (1919\u201341)===\n\nThe Chelsea Doughboy Statue, which cost $10,000, was donated by the Chelsea Memorial Committee and dedicated on April 7, 1921.{{sfn|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\nThe decorative gateposts commemorating Dowling, Goodwin, and Kavanagh were installed in 1926.{{sfn|GIVES TWO GATES TO CITY 1926}}\nOn August 18, 1925, a [[water tower]] from a nearby building collapsed on the park, injuring two children.{{sfn|TANK CRASH CAUSES CHELSEA PARK PANIC}}\n\nThe Department of Parks reconstructed a section of the park from 1934 and 1936, and it reopened on June 25, 1936.{{sfn|11 NEW PLAY AREAS WILL OPEN TODAY}}\nIn its announcement advertising the park's reopening, the Department of Parks said, \"\u2026the reconstructed area will have a large play area with one ball field, handball courts, complete play equipment for small children and a wading pool.\"{{sfn|Cruz|2016}}\nA {{convert|60|by|100|ft|m|adj=on}}, $175,000 health center for the middle of the park was proposed in 1935.{{sfn|Health Centre to Cost $175,000}} \nIts cost later grew to $264,000.{{sfn|MAYOR BARS PRAISE FOR HEALTH CENTER}}\nThe Lower West Side Health Center, as it was called, was built as part of the [[Public Works Administration]].{{sfn|MAYOR BARS PRAISE FOR HEALTH CENTER}}\nThe Health Center Building was opened to the public in July 1937.{{sfn|MAYOR BARS PRAISE FOR HEALTH CENTER}}\nIt was in the eastern part of the park and had a public playground on the roof.{{sfn|Cruz|2016}}\nThe Lower West Side Health Center was one of 8 clinics that were opened in the city that year,{{sfn|MAYOR BARS PRAISE FOR HEALTH CENTER}} \nout of a total of 30 health centers that had been proposed for the city.{{sfn|Health Center On West Side To Be Opened}}\nAt the time of its opening, there were 250,000 people living within the health center's service area.{{sfn|Health Center On West Side To Be Opened}}\n\nA proposal to demolish the P.S. 33 building and replace it with an extension of the park was rejected in 1938.{{sfn|BOARD ABANDONS PLAN 1938}} \nThe [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA) made further changes to the playground.\nThey added a new area of asphalt in the west of the park, \"graded so that it can be flooded for ice-skating when sub-freezing temperatures permit. In season it will be used for roller skating, roller hockey, softball, basketball and other group games.\"{{sfn|Parks Department Press Releases|1940|p=41 (PDF)}}\nThe WPA also built three [[basketball]] courts, three [[handball]] courts, two courts for pitching [[horseshoes]], and one for [[Skittles (sport)|skittles]].{{sfn|Cruz|2016}}{{sfn|Parks Department Press Releases|1940|p=41 (PDF)}}\nThis replaced the single baseball diamond that had formerly occupied that portion of the park.{{sfn|MAYOR REDEDICATES CHELSEA PLAYGROUND}}\nThe 1940 restoration added floodlights to the softball diamonds.{{sfn|P.O. David Willis Basketball Court}}\nThe children's playground was fully equipped with a large wading pool and brick washrooms, while the playground on the roof of the Health Center Building was converted to a sitting area.{{sfn|Parks Department Press Releases|1940|p=41 (PDF)}}\nThe WPA-restored park was officially opened on June 6, 1940 in a ceremony attended by Mayor [[Fiorello H. La Guardia]] and Parks Commissioner [[Robert Moses]].{{sfn|Cruz|2016}}{{sfn|MAYOR REDEDICATES CHELSEA PLAYGROUND}}\nAt the time, it was hoped that the existing P.S. 33 structure would be relocated at a future date so the park could be expanded.{{sfn|Parks Department Press Releases|1940|p=41 (PDF)}}\n\n===Postwar changes (1945\u2013present)===\n\nIn 1949, the [[New York City Planning Commission]] approved a project to add eight new recreation centers citywide, including a $450,000 indoor swimming pool in Chelsea Park,{{sfn|NEW PLAY CENTER|1949}} In November 1953, an extension to the park opened on the grounds of P.S.&nbsp;33.{{efn|A ''[[New York Times]]'' report and a press release from NYC Parks in November 1953 both announced the opening of the annex on that date.{{sfn|Chelsea Park Enlarged 1953}}{{sfn|Parks Department Press Releases|1953|p=158 (PDF)}} However, a more recent NYC Parks webpage says the extension on the grounds of P.S.&nbsp;33 opened in 1952.{{sfn|P.O. David Willis Basketball Court}}}}\nThe new additions included two handball courts, three basketball courts, and exercise equipment.{{sfn|Chelsea Park Enlarged 1953}}\n\nIn 1962, plans were announced to build a new post office annex between 28th and 29th Streets, immediately north of the park.\nThe location was occupied by 215 families at the time.{{sfn|Empty Block At Postal Annex|1979}}\nA fire in 1967 destroyed the Morgan Post Office Station, one block north of the park between 29th and 30th Streets.{{sfn|Empty Block At Postal Annex|1979}}{{sfn|Postal Annex Swept By Fire|1967}}\nAs of 1977 the park had recently been converted into an tarmac-based \"adventure park\" with a variety of playground equipment.\nThat year, an [[environmental impact assessment]] for the post office annex was conducted.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey|1977|p=21}}\nBy 1979, the post office station had not been rebuilt, and the block between 28th and 29th Streets had remained undeveloped for over a decade.{{sfn|Empty Block At Postal Annex|1979}}\nA postal truck facility planned for that block, which was canceled due to community opposition, was rebuilt at 11th Avenue between 24th and 26th Streets in 1988.{{sfn|Postal Trucks Find a Home|1988}}\n\nIn 1988 the park was well-used from April to November, and the baseball fields were often fully booked. \nCrime was not a serious problem.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-230}}\nThe park was being used by homeless people, particularly at the 9th Avenue end, which discouraged the residents of the neighborhood from using that part.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-233}}\nAn upgrade to the active play equipment in the center portion of the park was planned for the Fall of 1988.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-254}}\nIn January 1989 a final [[Environmental Impact Statement]] (FEIS) was published for a Manhattan General Mail Facility Complex across West 28th Street.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=i}}\nAs part of the FEIS, upgrades to the park were proposed.{{sfn|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a|p=IV-257}}\n\nThe playground and basketball courts were restored in the mid-1990s.{{sfn|P.O. David Willis Basketball Court}}\nThe park was again upgraded in the decade leading up to 2016, but the six handball courts remained dilapidated. \nThe New York City Parks Department, supported by the Fairway Community Foundation, finished refurbishment of the handball courts in 2016.\nHoles in the walls were patched up and the walls were repainted.\nThe city spent $127,000 on renovations of Chelsea Park as well as at [[Coffey Park]] in [[Red Hook, Brooklyn]].\nParks Department Commissioner [[Mitchell Silver]] was present at a ribbon-cutting ceremony for the handball courts in August 2016.{{sfn|Rajamani|2016}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252018%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Press%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Press%25201905%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Press%25201905%2520-%25200671.pdf\n |title=$4,000,000 VOTED FOR PARKS|last=|first=|date=June 30, 1906|work=New York Press|access-date=October 30, 2017\n |page=10|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]|ref={{harvid|$4,000,000 VOTED FOR PARKS}}}}\n*{{cite news | title=11 NEW PLAY AREAS WILL OPEN TODAY; Four of the Spots for Younger Children in Central Park -- Also Four in Brooklyn. MORE TO BE IN USE LATER Variety of Equipment Has Been Set Up -- Opening Tomorrow of New Jefferson Pool. | work=The New York Times | date=1936-06-26 | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1936/06/26/87953089.pdf | ref={{harvid|11 NEW PLAY AREAS WILL OPEN TODAY}} | access-date=2017-10-31}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/records/pdf/govpub/4101annual_report_nyc_dept_parks_1906.pdf|title=1906 New York City Department of Public Parks Annual Report|last=|first=|date=1906|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|pages=|access-date=October 30, 2017|ref={{sfnref|NYC Parks Annual Report|1906}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/records/pdf/govpub/4491annual_report_nyc_dept_parks_1907.pdf|title=1907 New York City Department of Public Parks Annual Report|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1907|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=October 30, 2017|ref={{sfnref|NYC Parks Annual Report|1907}}}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/records/pdf/govpub/4301annual_report_nyc_dept_parks_1908_part1.pdf|title=1908 New York City Department of Public Parks Annual Report, Part 1|last=|first=|date=1908|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=October 30, 2017|ref={{sfnref|NYC Parks Annual Report|1908}}}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/records/pdf/govpub/4026annual_report_nyc_dept_parks_1910.pdf\n |title=1910 New York City Department of Public Parks Annual Report |last= |first= |date=1910 |website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=October 30, 2017 |ref={{sfnref|NYC Parks Annual Report|1910}}}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/records/pdf/govpub/41941940_press_releases_part1.pdf|title=1940 Parks Department Press Releases (Part 1)|last= |first= |date=1940|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=October 30, 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Parks Department Press Releases|1940}}}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://home2.nyc.gov/html/records/pdf/govpub/42091953_press_releases_part1.pdf|title=1953 Parks Department Press Releases (Part 1)|last= |first= |date=1953|website=[[Government of New York City|nyc.gov]] |publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|access-date=October 30, 2017 |ref={{sfnref|Parks Department Press Releases|1953}}}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/09/09/120271232.pdf\n |title=A CHELSEA PLAYGROUND |last=|first=|date=September 9, 1904|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|A CHELSEA PLAYGROUND 1904}}}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/08/14/117946218.pdf\n |title=A WEST SIDE PARK |last=|first=|date=August 14, 1904|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 31, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|A WEST SIDE PARK 1904}}}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/03/02/104922859.pdf|title=ALL BARE PLOTS TO BE PLAYGROUNDS; Park Commissioner Stover Tells of His Plans to Make the Lives of Children Happier.|last=|first=|date=March 2, 1910|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 31, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{sfnref|ALL BARE PLOTS|1910}}}}\n* {{cite web | last=Asbury | first=Edith Evans | title=An Empty Block At Postal Annex Costing Millions | website=The New York Times | date=1979-04-09 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/04/09/archives/an-empty-block-at-postal-annex-costing-millions-residents-of.html | ref={{sfnref|Empty Block At Postal Annex|1979}}| access-date=2017-11-01}}\n*{{cite news | ref={{harvid|BOARD ABANDONS PLAN 1938}}\n |title=BOARD ABANDONS PLAN FOR SCHOOL IN PARK; Protests Against Building in Chelsea Area Result in Dropping of Project | work=The New York Times | date=1938-02-02\n |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1938/02/02/96792987.pdf | access-date=2017-10-31}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Chelsea Park \u2013 NYC Parks}}\n |title=Chelsea Park|publisher=NYC Parks\n |url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/chelsea-park|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Chelsea Park Memorial ... NYC Parks}}\n |title=Chelsea Park Memorial (Doughboy)|publisher=NYC Parks\n |url=https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/chelsea-park/monuments/232|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{Cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Tribune%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Tribune%25201907%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Tribune%25201907%252007-23%2520Page%25208.pdf\n |title=CHELSEA PARK DELAYED|last=|first=|date=July 23, 1907|work=New York Daily Tribune|access-date=October 30, 2017|page=8|via=[[Fultonhistory.com]]|ref={{harvid|CHELSEA PARK DELAYED}}}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1953/11/11/84074876.pdf\n |title=Chelsea Park Enlarged|last=|first=|date=November 11, 1953|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 30, 2017\n |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|Chelsea Park Enlarged 1953}} }}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/09/10/118948209.pdf\n |title=CHELSEA PARK OPPOSED.; Middle West Sider Argues for Block Further North.|last=|first=|date=September 10, 1904|work=The New York Times\n |access-date=October 30, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|ref={{harvid|CHELSEA PARK OPPOSED 1904}}}}\n*{{citation |title=Chelsea Park \u2013 New York NY\n |last=Cruz|first=Frank da  |date=October 6, 2016|work=Living New Deal\n |url=https://livingnewdeal.org/projects/chelsea-park-new-york-ny/|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{citation\n |author=Edwards and Kelcey|title=Manhattan Postal Station Vehicle Maintenance Facility: Environmental Impact Statement\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X9w3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA21|accessdate=October 30, 2017|year=1977}}\n*{{citation\n |author=Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|title=Manhattan General Mail Facility: Environmental Impact Statement\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ot03AQAAMAAJ&pg=PT36|volume=Volume 1|accessdate=October 30, 2017|year=1989|ref={{sfnref|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989a}}}}\n*{{citation\n |author=Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|title=Manhattan General Mail Facility: Environmental Impact Statement\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YN03AQAAMAAJ|volume=Volume 2: Appendix|accessdate=October 30, 2017|year=1989|ref={{sfnref|Edwards and Kelcey Engineers|1989b}}}}\n*{{citation\n |last=Fitzpatrick|first=Kevin C.|title=World War I New York: A Guide to the City's Enduring Ties to The Great War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=esctDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT73 \n |accessdate=October 30, 2017|date=April 20, 2017|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|isbn=978-1-4930-2804-7}}\n*{{citation|ref={{harvid|Frank L. Dowling ... Culture Now}} |title=Frank L. Dowling, William L. Kavanagh, Frank J. Goodwin, 1926 |work=Culture Now \n |url=http://culturenow.org/entry&permalink=03369&seo=Frank-L-Dowling-William-L-Kavanagh-Frank-J-Goodwin_Murry-and-Matheson-and-Unknown|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}\n*{{citation|title=Windows and Vegetation: Primary Factors in Manhattan Bird Collisions\n |last1=Gelb |last2=Delacretaz|first1=Yigal |first2=Nicole|journal