w York City}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chelsea Park}}\n[[Category:Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Parks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:1910 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chelsea_Park"}
{"title_page": "Tyne Bridge", "text_new": "{{For|the Parliamentary Constituency|Tyne Bridge (UK Parliament constituency)}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox bridge\n|image         = Tyne Bridge.jpg\n|name          = Tyne Bridge\n|caption       = Tyne Bridge looking towards the modern [[The Sage Gateshead|Sage Gateshead]] with the now moved [[Tuxedo Princess]] moored below. The banner is advertising the 2006 [[Great North Run]]\n|coordinates   = {{Coord|54.9680|-1.6060|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n|os_grid_reference = NZ253637\n|official_name = \n|other_name    = New Tyne Bridge<ref name=nhle />\n|locale        = [[Tyneside]]\n|carries       = {{ubl|{{UK road|A167}}|{{UK NCN route|route=725|regional=true}}}}\n|crosses       = [[River Tyne]]\n|owner         = {{ubl|[[Newcastle City Council]]|[[Gateshead Council]]}}\n|maint         = [[Newcastle City Council|Newcastle]]{{endash}}[[Gateshead Council|Gateshead]] Bridges Joint Committee\n|heritage      = [[Grade II* listed]]<ref name=nhle />\n|preceded      = [[Swing Bridge, River Tyne|Swing Bridge]]\n|followed      = [[Gateshead Millennium Bridge]]\n|begin         = August 1925\n|complete      = 25 February 1928\n|open          = \n|inaugurated   = {{ubl|10 October 1928|by [[King George V]]}}\n|below         = {{cvt|26|m|order=flip}}\n|traffic       = approx. 70,000 vehicles\n|design        = [[Through arch bridge]]\n|material      = Steel\n|material2     = Cornish [[granite]]\n|mainspan      = {{cvt|161.8|m|order=flip}}\n|lanes         = 4\n|architect     = [[Robert Burns Dick]]\n|designer      = [[Mott, Hay and Anderson]]\n|builder       = [[Dorman Long|Dorman Long and Co.]]\n|fabricator    = \n|length        = {{cvt|389|m|order=flip}}\n|width         = {{cvt|17|m|order=flip}}\n|map_type      = Tyne and Wear\n|map_relief    = no\n}}\n\nThe '''Tyne Bridge''' is a [[through arch bridge]] over the [[River Tyne]] in [[North East England]], linking [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] and [[Gateshead]]. The bridge was designed by the engineering firm [[Mott, Hay and Anderson]],<ref name=TyneBridge201407>{{cite web | last = Elwall |first=Robert |title=Tyne Bridge |publisher=British Architectural Library |url=http://www.architecture.com/Explore/Buildings/TyneBridge.aspx |access-date=14 July 2014}}</ref> who later designed the [[Forth Road Bridge]], and was built by [[Dorman Long|Dorman Long and Co.]] of [[Middlesbrough]].<ref name=DLong201407>{{cite web |title=Dorman Long Historical Information |website=dormanlongtechnology.com |url=http://www.dormanlongtechnology.com/en/Dorman%20Long%20historical%20information.htm |access-date=14 July 2014 }}</ref> The bridge was officially opened on 10 October 1928 by King [[George V of the United Kingdom|George V]] and has since become a defining symbol of [[Tyneside]]. It is ranked as the [[List of tallest buildings and structures in Newcastle upon Tyne|tenth tallest structure in the city]].\n\n\n\n\nHeyyyyy it\u2019s cynthia\n\n==History of construction==\n[[File:High Level and Low Level bridges - Newcastle - 1861.jpg|left|thumb|The 1781 stone bridge, with the [[High Level Bridge]] in the background, from an 1861 illustration]]\n\n[[File:Side - Tyne Bridge.jpg|left|thumb|Tyne Bridge viewed from [[Quayside]]]]\nThe earliest bridge across the Tyne, [[Pons Aelius]], was built by the Romans on the site of the present [[Swing Bridge, River Tyne|Swing Bridge]] around 122.<ref name=PonsAelius>{{cite web|title=Pons Aelius - 'The Aelian Bridge'|publisher=roman-britain.co.uk |url=http://roman-britain.co.uk/places/pons_aelius.htm |access-date=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nWork started in August 1925 with [[Dorman Long]] acting as the building contractors. Despite the dangers of the building work, only one worker, Nathaniel Collins, a father of four and a local scaffolder from [[South Shields]], died in the building of this structure.<ref name=TyneBridge201407-2>{{cite web |last=Butcher |first=Joanne |title=85 years of the Tyne Bridge |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=1 March 2013 |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/85-years-tyne-bridge-crossing-1724495 |access-date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Tyne Bridge was designed by [[Mott, Hay and Anderson]], comparable to their [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] version.<ref name=TyneBridge201407/><ref name=sHarbNewc/> These bridges derived their design from the [[Hell Gate Bridge]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=sHarbNewc/> The Dorman Long team was also notable for including Dorothy Buchanan, the first female member of the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], joining in 1927; in addition to her contribution to the Tyne Bridge, she served as part of the team for the Sydney Harbour Bridge and the [[Lambeth Bridge]] in London.<ref> {{cite web |last=Chapman|first=Tegan|date=10 October 2018|title=Female engineers gather to celebrate the Tyne Bridge turning 90 |url=https://www.ice.org.uk/news-and-insight/latest-ice-news/ice-north-east-celebrates-tyne-bridge-birthday|publisher=[[Institution of Civil Engineers]]|access-date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was completed on 25 February 1928, and officially opened on 10 October by King George V and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]], who were the first to use the roadway, travelling in their [[Ascot (1928 automobile)|Ascot]] Landau. The opening ceremony was attended by 20,000 schoolchildren who had been given the day off.  Movietone news recorded the speech given by the King.<ref name=NewGats2014>{{cite news |last=Butcher |first=Joanne |title=Bridge spans the generations |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=26 February 2013 |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/85-years-tyne-bridge-bridge-1724342 |access-date=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Tyne Bridge's towers were built of Cornish [[granite]] and were designed by local architect [[Robert Burns Dick]]<ref name=TyneBridge201407/> as warehouses with five storeys. But, the inner floors of the warehouses in the bridge's towers were not completed and, as a result, the storage areas were never used. Lifts for passengers and goods were built in the towers to provide access to the [[Quayside]]; they are no longer in use.<ref name=BOTT:TTB>{{Cite web |title=The Tyne Bridge |work=Bridges on the Tyne |year=2006 |url=http://www.bridgesonthetyne.co.uk/tynebri.html |access-date=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge's design uses a [[parabolic arch]].<ref name=sHarbNewc>{{cite web |title=Tyne Bridge |website=BBC Inside Out |date=24 September 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/northeast/series3/tyne_bridge_northeasthistory.shtml |access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was originally painted green with special paint made by J. Dampney Co. of Gateshead. The same colours were used to paint the bridge in 2000.<ref name=\"CL:EFYotTB\">{{Cite news |last=Butcher |first=Joanne |title=85 years of the Tyne Bridge: Crossing of the great divide |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |access-date=20 October 2016 |date=1 March 2013 |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/85-years-tyne-bridge-crossing-1724495}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyne bridge 1928.jpg|300px|thumb|Tyne Bridge under construction in 1928]]\n\n==Technical Information==\n<ref name=tyneBTech>{{cite web\n | url = https://structurae.net/structures/tyne-bridge\n | title = Tyne Bridge - Technical Information\n | website = structurae.net\n | publisher = International Database for Civil and Structural Engineering \n | access-date = 22 May 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n|+ \n|-\n| '''Total length''' || {{convert|389|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Length of arch span'''  || {{convert|161.8|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Rise of arch''' || {{convert|55|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Clearance'''  || {{convert|26|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Height'''  || {{convert|59|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Width''' || {{convert|17.08|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Structural Steel'''  || {{convert|7,122|tonnes|LT|order=flip}}\n|-\t\n| '''Total number of rivets'''<ref name=GOPH>{{cite web | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=C-WGCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1928&lpg=PA1928&source=bl&ots=9LTQhb64cu&sig=_NHoJm2chHLzobdUgy9nhF32vm8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiRwrzw_tPeAhXuqIsKHT1FAQIQ6AEwAHoECAwQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false\n | title = Gateshead from Old Photographs\n | publisher = Amberley Publishing\n | access-date = 14 Nov 2018\n | quote = }}</ref> || 777,124\n|}\n\n==History of operations==\n[[File:Tyne Bridge - Newcastle Upon Tyne - England - 2004-08-14.jpg|thumbnail|right|300px|The Tyne Bridge, in green, seen from the [[Gateshead Millennium Bridge]]]]\n[[File:Tyne Bridge Olympics.jpg|thumbnail|right|The Olympic rings on the bridge]]\n[[File:PZarobkiewiczTyneNewcastle 01.jpg|thumb|right|A night view of the Tyne Bridge taken from the northern embankment, looking west]]\n\nIn 2012 the largest [[Olympic rings]] in the UK were erected on the bridge. The rings were manufactured by commercial signage specialists Signmaster ED Ltd of Kelso. The rings were over {{convert|25|by|12|metres}} and weighed in excess of four tonnes. This was in preparation for Newcastle hosting the Olympic football tournament, and the Olympic torch relay, in which [[Bear Grylls]] zipwired from the top of the arch, to Gateshead quayside.<ref>{{cite news |title=Olympic rings launched on Tyne Bridge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-18432414 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=13 June 2012 |access-date=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2012, a large lightning bolt struck the Tyne Bridge. It lit up the roads as the sky was very dark. The bolt, part of a super-cell thunderstorm, came with heavy rain \u2013 a month's worth of rainfall in just two hours \u2013 causing flash flooding on Tyneside.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hough |first=Andrew |title=Weather: record 110,000 lightning bolts strike during 'superstorms' |newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=[[London]] |access-date=20 October 2016 |date=29 June 2012 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/weather/9365699/Weather-record-110000-lightning-bolts-strike-during-superstorms.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Newcastle upon Tyne was a host city for the Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/cities/newcastle/ |title=Host Cities: Newcastle |publisher=Rugby World Cup |date=2015 |access-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210212720/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/cities/newcastle/ |archivedate=10 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Three matches were played at St James's Park, the home of Newcastle United Football Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/venues/st-james-park |title=St James' Park |publisher=Rugby World Cup |date=2015 |access-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207171144/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/venues/st-james-park |archivedate=7 December 2015 }}</ref> In recognition, a large illuminated sign was erected on Tyne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/rugby-world-cup-2015-tyne-8672958 |title=Rugby World Cup 2015: Tyne Bridge sign to be replaced with Great North Run advert |first=Katie |last=Davies |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=18 February 2015 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 November 2017, the Tyne Bridge was the venue for the Freedom on the Tyne finale, the finale of the 2017 Freedom City festival. The 2017 Freedom City festival commemorated Newcastle's civil rights history and the 50 years since [[Martin_Luther_King_Jr.|Dr Martin Luther King's]] visit to Newcastle, where King received his honorary degree from [[Newcastle University]].<ref name=freedomCity2017_1>{{cite news | last = Whetstone | first = David | title = Newcastle's iconic Tyne Bridge is to host the spectacular Freedom on the Tyne finale| newspaper = [[Newcastle Chronicle]] | language = English | publisher = [[Trinity Mirror]] | date = 4 October 2017 | url = https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/newcastles-iconic-tyne-bridge-host-13715946| access-date = 11 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=honDegreeKing>{{cite news | last = Whetstone | first = David | title = Statue of Dr Martin Luther King has been unveiled in Newcastle by his great friend| newspaper = [[Newcastle Chronicle]] | publisher = [[Trinity Mirror]] | date = 13 November 2017 | url = https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/statue-dr-martin-luther-king-13896213| access-date = 11 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=freedomCity>{{cite web | url = http://freedomcity2017.com/ | title = Freedom City 2017 | last = freedomCity2017 Staff | website = freedomcity2017.com | publisher = [[Newcastle University]] | access-date = 11 July 2018 | quote = }}</ref>\n\nNewcastle University and Freedom City 2017 wanted to use the Tyne Bridge to symbolically hark back in history to [[Edmund Pettus Bridge]] in [[Selma, Alabama]] where King was involved in one of the key moments for the struggle for civil rights in 1965.<ref name=freedomCity2017_1/> 24 roads around the Tyne Bridge where closed for the day long event. The Freedom of the Tyne event featured the many civil right stories from history.<ref name=freedomCity2017_1/> The final event, revolved around the [[Jarrow Crusade]] which was described as a memorable closing to the finale.<ref name=freedomCity2017_1/>\n\n==Grade II* listed by Historic England==\nOn the 23 August 2018 the bridge became one of the 5.8% of structures in England which are [[Listed building#England and Wales|Grade II* listed]]. The rating means the bridge is ''a particular important structure of more than special interest.''<ref name=gradeII*>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-tyne-45276022/tyne-bridge-upgraded-to-grade-ii-by-historic-england | title = Tyne Bridge upgraded to Grade II* by Historic England | date = 23 August 2018 | website = [[BBC News]] | publisher = [[BBC]] | access-date = 23 August 2018 | quote =  was a \"representation of the North East's steely attitude\",...; \"it fully deserves to be among the 5.8% of structures which are Grade II* listed\". }}</ref> The bridge was upgraded by the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport on the advice of Historic England.<ref name=chronGradeII>{{cite news | last = Henderson | first = Tony | title = We all know the Tyne Bridge symbolises greatness - but there's now proof | newspaper = [[Newcastle Chronicle]] | publisher = [[Trinity Mirror]] | date = 23 August 2018 | url = https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/know-tyne-bridge-symbolises-greatness-15061652 | access-date = 24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was upgraded to Grade II* for architectural and historical interest,<ref name=nhle>{{NHLE |num=1248569 |desc=Tyne Bridge |grade=II* |access-date=2018-09-05}}</ref> as outlined here:\n\n{{quote|Architectural interest:\nA striking steel arch design, at its construction, notable as the largest single-span steel arch bridge on the British Isles; It is a similar prototype design as to that prepared for Sydney Harbour, Australia; the main arch was designed by the eminent civil engineer (Sir) Ralph Freeman; the prototype of a method of construction involving progressive cantilevering, using cables, cradles and cranes, which was also developed for Sydney Harbour, but first tested in Newcastle; its neoclassical and Art Deco towers that are well-detailed and defined; a potent symbol of the character and industrial pride of Tyneside; recognised worldwide for its dramatic design.<ref name=LAAuthGradeII/>}}\n\n{{quote|Historic interest: \nit is associated with some of the most distinguished 20th-century civil engineers. One of its engineers being Sir Ralph Freeman, the architect of some of the most impressive bridges in the world. Freeman was a founder of Freeman Fox & Partners, renowned bridge designers worldwide.<ref name=LAAuthGradeII>{{cite web | url = https://www.newcastle.gov.uk/news/tyne-bridge-listed-status-upgraded-during-great-exhibition-north-celebrate-its-importance | title = Tyne Bridge listed status upgraded during Great Exhibition Of The North to celebrate its importance | date = 23 August 2018  | website = newcastle.gov.uk | publisher = [[Newcastle City Council]] | access-date = 24 August 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n==Kittiwake colony==\nThe bridge and nearby structures are used as a nesting site by a colony of around 700 pairs of [[black-legged kittiwake]]s, the furthest inland in the world. The colony featured in the BBC's ''[[Springwatch]]'' programme in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p007yfpf |title=Tynesiders |work=Springwatch |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=19 May 2010 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref> Several groups, including the Natural History Society of Northumbria and local Wildlife Trusts, formed a \"Tyne Kittiwake Partnership\" to safeguard the colony.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhsn.ncl.ac.uk/news/cms/tynekittiwakes/ |title=Tyne Kittiwakes Partnership |publisher=Natural History Society of Northumbria |year=2016 |accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> A proposal for a tower to be built as an alternative nesting site was made in 2011,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/17/newcastle-kittiwake-gull-colony |title=Newcastle in a flap over urban kittiwake colony |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |first=Martin |last=Wainwright |date=17 May 2011 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref> and in November 2015 a neighbouring hotel submitted a planning application for measures to discourage the birds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publicaccessapplications.newcastle.gov.uk/online-applications/applicationDetails.do?activeTab=summary&keyVal=NXK4MVBSM8N00 |title=Installation of bird netting, angled sill plates and avishock system to tower \u2013 Tyne Bridge Tower Lombard Street Newcastle upon Tyne |website=[[Newcastle City Council]] |date=9 November 2015 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Addyman, J. and Fawcett, B. ''The High Level Bridge and Newcastle Central Station: 150 Years Across the Tyne''. By the North Eastern Railway Association for the High Level Bridge. 1999. {{ISBN|1-873513-28-3}}.\n* Linsley, S. ''Spanning the Tyne: Building of the Tyne Bridge, 1925-28''. Newcastle Libraries and Information Service, Newcastle City Council. 1998. {{ISBN|1-85795-009-7}}.\n* Manders, F. & Potts, R. ''Crossing the Tyne''. Tyne Bridge Publishing. 2001. {{ISBN|1-85795-121-2}}.\n* Anderson, D. Tyne Bridge, Newcastle in \"Proceedings of the Institution of Civil Engineers\", March 1930 v. 230 \n* Prade, Marcel Les grands ponts du monde: Ponts remarquables d'Europe, Brissaud, Poitiers (France), {{ISBN|2902170653}}, 1990; pp.&nbsp;274\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tyne Bridge}}\n* Databases: [http://www.bridgesonthetyne.co.uk Bridges On The Tyne], [https://web.archive.org/web/20120404195418/http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=28 Engineering Timelines], and {{Structurae|id=20001255}}\n* Articles: [https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/northeast/series3/tyne_bridge_northeasthistory.shtml BBC Inside Out - Tyne Bridge]\n* {{oscoor gbx|NZ253637}}.\n\n;Images\n* Historic photographs:  [https://web.archive.org/web/20050310225320/http://www.amber-online.com/gallery/exhibition29/ Dorman Long collection], [http://www.picturesofgateshead.co.uk/postcards_tyne_bridge_uc/index.html Pictures of Gateshead]\n* Aerial photographs: [http://www.britainfromabove.org.uk/image/epw019832 Britain from Above] - aerial views of the bridge under construction and later in the 1930s, from the [[Aerofilms]] archive of [[English Heritage]]\n* Photographs of Tyne Bridges: [http://www.peterloud.co.uk/photos/Newcastle/Nc_4.html Peter Loud]\n* Video: [https://www.bbc.co.uk/nationonfilm/topics/misc-work/tyne-bridge-construction-building.shtml BBC - Nation on Film]\n\n{{River item box\n|River      = [[River Tyne]]\n|upstream   = [[Swing Bridge, River Tyne|Swing Bridge]]\n|downstream = [[Gateshead Millennium Bridge]]\n|downsub    = [[Footbridge]]\n|location   = NZ253637}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1928]]\n[[Category:Transport in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Through arch bridges in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Crossings of the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed bridges]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Parliamentary Constituency|Tyne Bridge (UK Parliament constituency)}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox bridge\n|image         = Tyne Bridge.jpg\n|name          = Tyne Bridge\n|caption       = Tyne Bridge looking towards the modern [[The Sage Gateshead|Sage Gateshead]] with the now moved [[Tuxedo Princess]] moored below. The banner is advertising the 2006 [[Great North Run]]\n|coordinates   = {{Coord|54.9680|-1.6060|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n|os_grid_reference = NZ253637\n|official_name = \n|other_name    = New Tyne Bridge<ref name=nhle />\n|locale        = [[Tyneside]]\n|carries       = {{ubl|{{UK road|A167}}|{{UK NCN route|route=725|regional=true}}}}\n|crosses       = [[River Tyne]]\n|owner         = {{ubl|[[Newcastle City Council]]|[[Gateshead Council]]}}\n|maint         = [[Newcastle City Council|Newcastle]]{{endash}}[[Gateshead Council|Gateshead]] Bridges Joint Committee\n|heritage      = [[Grade II* listed]]<ref name=nhle />\n|preceded      = [[Swing Bridge, River Tyne|Swing Bridge]]\n|followed      = [[Gateshead Millennium Bridge]]\n|begin         = August 1925\n|complete      = 25 February 1928\n|open          = \n|inaugurated   = {{ubl|10 October 1928|by [[King George V]]}}\n|below         = {{cvt|26|m|order=flip}}\n|traffic       = approx. 70,000 vehicles\n|design        = [[Through arch bridge]]\n|material      = Steel\n|material2     = Cornish [[granite]]\n|mainspan      = {{cvt|161.8|m|order=flip}}\n|lanes         = 4\n|architect     = [[Robert Burns Dick]]\n|designer      = [[Mott, Hay and Anderson]]\n|builder       = [[Dorman Long|Dorman Long and Co.]]\n|fabricator    = \n|length        = {{cvt|389|m|order=flip}}\n|width         = {{cvt|17|m|order=flip}}\n|map_type      = Tyne and Wear\n|map_relief    = no\n}}\n\nThe '''Tyne Bridge''' is a [[through arch bridge]] over the [[River Tyne]] in [[North East England]], linking [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] and [[Gateshead]]. The bridge was designed by the engineering firm [[Mott, Hay and Anderson]],<ref name=TyneBridge201407>{{cite web | last = Elwall |first=Robert |title=Tyne Bridge |publisher=British Architectural Library |url=http://www.architecture.com/Explore/Buildings/TyneBridge.aspx |access-date=14 July 2014}}</ref> who later designed the [[Forth Road Bridge]], and was built by [[Dorman Long|Dorman Long and Co.]] of [[Middlesbrough]].<ref name=DLong201407>{{cite web |title=Dorman Long Historical Information |website=dormanlongtechnology.com |url=http://www.dormanlongtechnology.com/en/Dorman%20Long%20historical%20information.htm |access-date=14 July 2014 }}</ref> The bridge was officially opened on 10 October 1928 by King [[George V of the United Kingdom|George V]] and has since become a defining symbol of [[Tyneside]]. It is ranked as the [[List of tallest buildings and structures in Newcastle upon Tyne|tenth tallest structure in the city]].\n\n==History of construction==\n[[File:High Level and Low Level bridges - Newcastle - 1861.jpg|left|thumb|The 1781 stone bridge, with the [[High Level Bridge]] in the background, from an 1861 illustration]]\n\n[[File:Side - Tyne Bridge.jpg|left|thumb|Tyne Bridge viewed from [[Quayside]]]]\nThe earliest bridge across the Tyne, [[Pons Aelius]], was built by the Romans on the site of the present [[Swing Bridge, River Tyne|Swing Bridge]] around 122.<ref name=PonsAelius>{{cite web|title=Pons Aelius - 'The Aelian Bridge'|publisher=roman-britain.co.uk |url=http://roman-britain.co.uk/places/pons_aelius.htm |access-date=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nWork started in August 1925 with [[Dorman Long]] acting as the building contractors. Despite the dangers of the building work, only one worker, Nathaniel Collins, a father of four and a local scaffolder from [[South Shields]], died in the building of this structure.<ref name=TyneBridge201407-2>{{cite web |last=Butcher |first=Joanne |title=85 years of the Tyne Bridge |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=1 March 2013 |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/85-years-tyne-bridge-crossing-1724495 |access-date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Tyne Bridge was designed by [[Mott, Hay and Anderson]], comparable to their [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] version.<ref name=TyneBridge201407/><ref name=sHarbNewc/> These bridges derived their design from the [[Hell Gate Bridge]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=sHarbNewc/> The Dorman Long team was also notable for including Dorothy Buchanan, the first female member of the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], joining in 1927; in addition to her contribution to the Tyne Bridge, she served as part of the team for the Sydney Harbour Bridge and the [[Lambeth Bridge]] in London.<ref> {{cite web |last=Chapman|first=Tegan|date=10 October 2018|title=Female engineers gather to celebrate the Tyne Bridge turning 90 |url=https://www.ice.org.uk/news-and-insight/latest-ice-news/ice-north-east-celebrates-tyne-bridge-birthday|publisher=[[Institution of Civil Engineers]]|access-date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was completed on 25 February 1928, and officially opened on 10 October by King George V and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]], who were the first to use the roadway, travelling in their [[Ascot (1928 automobile)|Ascot]] Landau. The opening ceremony was attended by 20,000 schoolchildren who had been given the day off.  Movietone news recorded the speech given by the King.<ref name=NewGats2014>{{cite news |last=Butcher |first=Joanne |title=Bridge spans the generations |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=26 February 2013 |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/85-years-tyne-bridge-bridge-1724342 |access-date=24 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Tyne Bridge's towers were built of Cornish [[granite]] and were designed by local architect [[Robert Burns Dick]]<ref name=TyneBridge201407/> as warehouses with five storeys. But, the inner floors of the warehouses in the bridge's towers were not completed and, as a result, the storage areas were never used. Lifts for passengers and goods were built in the towers to provide access to the [[Quayside]]; they are no longer in use.<ref name=BOTT:TTB>{{Cite web |title=The Tyne Bridge |work=Bridges on the Tyne |year=2006 |url=http://www.bridgesonthetyne.co.uk/tynebri.html |access-date=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge's design uses a [[parabolic arch]].<ref name=sHarbNewc>{{cite web |title=Tyne Bridge |website=BBC Inside Out |date=24 September 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/northeast/series3/tyne_bridge_northeasthistory.shtml |access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was originally painted green with special paint made by J. Dampney Co. of Gateshead. The same colours were used to paint the bridge in 2000.<ref name=\"CL:EFYotTB\">{{Cite news |last=Butcher |first=Joanne |title=85 years of the Tyne Bridge: Crossing of the great divide |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |access-date=20 October 2016 |date=1 March 2013 |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/85-years-tyne-bridge-crossing-1724495}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyne bridge 1928.jpg|300px|thumb|Tyne Bridge under construction in 1928]]\n\n==Technical Information==\n<ref name=tyneBTech>{{cite web\n | url = https://structurae.net/structures/tyne-bridge\n | title = Tyne Bridge - Technical Information\n | website = structurae.net\n | publisher = International Database for Civil and Structural Engineering \n | access-date = 22 May 2017\n | quote = }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n|+ \n|-\n| '''Total length''' || {{convert|389|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Length of arch span'''  || {{convert|161.8|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Rise of arch''' || {{convert|55|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Clearance'''  || {{convert|26|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Height'''  || {{convert|59|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Width''' || {{convert|17.08|m|order=flip}}\n|-\n| '''Structural Steel'''  || {{convert|7,122|tonnes|LT|order=flip}}\n|-\t\n| '''Total number of rivets'''<ref name=GOPH>{{cite web | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=C-WGCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1928&lpg=PA1928&source=bl&ots=9LTQhb64cu&sig=_NHoJm2chHLzobdUgy9nhF32vm8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiRwrzw_tPeAhXuqIsKHT1FAQIQ6AEwAHoECAwQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false\n | title = Gateshead from Old Photographs\n | publisher = Amberley Publishing\n | access-date = 14 Nov 2018\n | quote = }}</ref> || 777,124\n|}\n\n==History of operations==\n[[File:Tyne Bridge - Newcastle Upon Tyne - England - 2004-08-14.jpg|thumbnail|right|300px|The Tyne Bridge, in green, seen from the [[Gateshead Millennium Bridge]]]]\n[[File:Tyne Bridge Olympics.jpg|thumbnail|right|The Olympic rings on the bridge]]\n[[File:PZarobkiewiczTyneNewcastle 01.jpg|thumb|right|A night view of the Tyne Bridge taken from the northern embankment, looking west]]\n\nIn 2012 the largest [[Olympic rings]] in the UK were erected on the bridge. The rings were manufactured by commercial signage specialists Signmaster ED Ltd of Kelso. The rings were over {{convert|25|by|12|metres}} and weighed in excess of four tonnes. This was in preparation for Newcastle hosting the Olympic football tournament, and the Olympic torch relay, in which [[Bear Grylls]] zipwired from the top of the arch, to Gateshead quayside.<ref>{{cite news |title=Olympic rings launched on Tyne Bridge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-18432414 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=13 June 2012 |access-date=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2012, a large lightning bolt struck the Tyne Bridge. It lit up the roads as the sky was very dark. The bolt, part of a super-cell thunderstorm, came with heavy rain \u2013 a month's worth of rainfall in just two hours \u2013 causing flash flooding on Tyneside.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hough |first=Andrew |title=Weather: record 110,000 lightning bolts strike during 'superstorms' |newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=[[London]] |access-date=20 October 2016 |date=29 June 2012 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/weather/9365699/Weather-record-110000-lightning-bolts-strike-during-superstorms.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Newcastle upon Tyne was a host city for the Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/cities/newcastle/ |title=Host Cities: Newcastle |publisher=Rugby World Cup |date=2015 |access-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210212720/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/cities/newcastle/ |archivedate=10 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Three matches were played at St James's Park, the home of Newcastle United Football Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/venues/st-james-park |title=St James' Park |publisher=Rugby World Cup |date=2015 |access-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207171144/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/venues/st-james-park |archivedate=7 December 2015 }}</ref> In recognition, a large illuminated sign was erected on Tyne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/rugby-world-cup-2015-tyne-8672958 |title=Rugby World Cup 2015: Tyne Bridge sign to be replaced with Great North Run advert |first=Katie |last=Davies |newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=18 February 2015 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 November 2017, the Tyne Bridge was the venue for the Freedom on the Tyne finale, the finale of the 2017 Freedom City festival. The 2017 Freedom City festival commemorated Newcastle's civil rights history and the 50 years since [[Martin_Luther_King_Jr.|Dr Martin Luther King's]] visit to Newcastle, where King received his honorary degree from [[Newcastle University]].<ref name=freedomCity2017_1>{{cite news | last = Whetstone | first = David | title = Newcastle's iconic Tyne Bridge is to host the spectacular Freedom on the Tyne finale| newspaper = [[Newcastle Chronicle]] | language = English | publisher = [[Trinity Mirror]] | date = 4 October 2017 | url = https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/newcastles-iconic-tyne-bridge-host-13715946| access-date = 11 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=honDegreeKing>{{cite news | last = Whetstone | first = David | title = Statue of Dr Martin Luther King has been unveiled in Newcastle by his great friend| newspaper = [[Newcastle Chronicle]] | publisher = [[Trinity Mirror]] | date = 13 November 2017 | url = https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/statue-dr-martin-luther-king-13896213| access-date = 11 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=freedomCity>{{cite web | url = http://freedomcity2017.com/ | title = Freedom City 2017 | last = freedomCity2017 Staff | website = freedomcity2017.com | publisher = [[Newcastle University]] | access-date = 11 July 2018 | quote = }}</ref>\n\nNewcastle University and Freedom City 2017 wanted to use the Tyne Bridge to symbolically hark back in history to [[Edmund Pettus Bridge]] in [[Selma, Alabama]] where King was involved in one of the key moments for the struggle for civil rights in 1965.<ref name=freedomCity2017_1/> 24 roads around the Tyne Bridge where closed for the day long event. The Freedom of the Tyne event featured the many civil right stories from history.<ref name=freedomCity2017_1/> The final event, revolved around the [[Jarrow Crusade]] which was described as a memorable closing to the finale.<ref name=freedomCity2017_1/>\n\n==Grade II* listed by Historic England==\nOn the 23 August 2018 the bridge became one of the 5.8% of structures in England which are [[Listed building#England and Wales|Grade II* listed]]. The rating means the bridge is ''a particular important structure of more than special interest.''<ref name=gradeII*>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-tyne-45276022/tyne-bridge-upgraded-to-grade-ii-by-historic-england | title = Tyne Bridge upgraded to Grade II* by Historic England | date = 23 August 2018 | website = [[BBC News]] | publisher = [[BBC]] | access-date = 23 August 2018 | quote =  was a \"representation of the North East's steely attitude\",...; \"it fully deserves to be among the 5.8% of structures which are Grade II* listed\". }}</ref> The bridge was upgraded by the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport on the advice of Historic England.<ref name=chronGradeII>{{cite news | last = Henderson | first = Tony | title = We all know the Tyne Bridge symbolises greatness - but there's now proof | newspaper = [[Newcastle Chronicle]] | publisher = [[Trinity Mirror]] | date = 23 August 2018 | url = https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/know-tyne-bridge-symbolises-greatness-15061652 | access-date = 24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge was upgraded to Grade II* for architectural and historical interest,<ref name=nhle>{{NHLE |num=1248569 |desc=Tyne Bridge |grade=II* |access-date=2018-09-05}}</ref> as outlined here:\n\n{{quote|Architectural interest:\nA striking steel arch design, at its construction, notable as the largest single-span steel arch bridge on the British Isles; It is a similar prototype design as to that prepared for Sydney Harbour, Australia; the main arch was designed by the eminent civil engineer (Sir) Ralph Freeman; the prototype of a method of construction involving progressive cantilevering, using cables, cradles and cranes, which was also developed for Sydney Harbour, but first tested in Newcastle; its neoclassical and Art Deco towers that are well-detailed and defined; a potent symbol of the character and industrial pride of Tyneside; recognised worldwide for its dramatic design.<ref name=LAAuthGradeII/>}}\n\n{{quote|Historic interest: \nit is associated with some of the most distinguished 20th-century civil engineers. One of its engineers being Sir Ralph Freeman, the architect of some of the most impressive bridges in the world. Freeman was a founder of Freeman Fox & Partners, renowned bridge designers worldwide.<ref name=LAAuthGradeII>{{cite web | url = https://www.newcastle.gov.uk/news/tyne-bridge-listed-status-upgraded-during-great-exhibition-north-celebrate-its-importance | title = Tyne Bridge listed status upgraded during Great Exhibition Of The North to celebrate its importance | date = 23 August 2018  | website = newcastle.gov.uk | publisher = [[Newcastle City Council]] | access-date = 24 August 2018}}</ref>}}\n\n==Kittiwake colony==\nThe bridge and nearby structures are used as a nesting site by a colony of around 700 pairs of [[black-legged kittiwake]]s, the furthest inland in the world. The colony featured in the BBC's ''[[Springwatch]]'' programme in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p007yfpf |title=Tynesiders |work=Springwatch |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=19 May 2010 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref> Several groups, including the Natural History Society of Northumbria and local Wildlife Trusts, formed a \"Tyne Kittiwake Partnership\" to safeguard the colony.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhsn.ncl.ac.uk/news/cms/tynekittiwakes/ |title=Tyne Kittiwakes Partnership |publisher=Natural History Society of Northumbria |year=2016 |accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> A proposal for a tower to be built as an alternative nesting site was made in 2011,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/17/newcastle-kittiwake-gull-colony |title=Newcastle in a flap over urban kittiwake colony |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |first=Martin |last=Wainwright |date=17 May 2011 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref> and in November 2015 a neighbouring hotel submitted a planning application for measures to discourage the birds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publicaccessapplications.newcastle.gov.uk/online-applications/applicationDetails.do?activeTab=summary&keyVal=NXK4MVBSM8N00 |title=Installation of bird netting, angled sill plates and avishock system to tower \u2013 Tyne Bridge Tower Lombard Street Newcastle upon Tyne |website=[[Newcastle City Council]] |date=9 November 2015 |access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Addyman, J. and Fawcett, B. ''The High Level Bridge and Newcastle Central Station: 150 Years Across the Tyne''. By the North Eastern Railway Association for the High Level Bridge. 1999. {{ISBN|1-873513-28-3}}.\n* Linsley, S. ''Spanning the Tyne: Building of the Tyne Bridge, 1925-28''. Newcastle Libraries and Information Service, Newcastle City Council. 1998. {{ISBN|1-85795-009-7}}.\n* Manders, F. & Potts, R. ''Crossing the Tyne''. Tyne Bridge Publishing. 2001. {{ISBN|1-85795-121-2}}.\n* Anderson, D. Tyne Bridge, Newcastle in \"Proceedings of the Institution of Civil Engineers\", March 1930 v. 230 \n* Prade, Marcel Les grands ponts du monde: Ponts remarquables d'Europe, Brissaud, Poitiers (France), {{ISBN|2902170653}}, 1990; pp.&nbsp;274\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tyne Bridge}}\n* Databases: [http://www.bridgesonthetyne.co.uk Bridges On The Tyne], [https://web.archive.org/web/20120404195418/http://www.engineering-timelines.com/scripts/engineeringItem.asp?id=28 Engineering Timelines], and {{Structurae|id=20001255}}\n* Articles: [https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/northeast/series3/tyne_bridge_northeasthistory.shtml BBC Inside Out - Tyne Bridge]\n* {{oscoor gbx|NZ253637}}.\n\n;Images\n* Historic photographs:  [https://web.archive.org/web/20050310225320/http://www.amber-online.com/gallery/exhibition29/ Dorman Long collection], [http://www.picturesofgateshead.co.uk/postcards_tyne_bridge_uc/index.html Pictures of Gateshead]\n* Aerial photographs: [http://www.britainfromabove.org.uk/image/epw019832 Britain from Above] - aerial views of the bridge under construction and later in the 1930s, from the [[Aerofilms]] archive of [[English Heritage]]\n* Photographs of Tyne Bridges: [http://www.peterloud.co.uk/photos/Newcastle/Nc_4.html Peter Loud]\n* Video: [https://www.bbc.co.uk/nationonfilm/topics/misc-work/tyne-bridge-construction-building.shtml BBC - Nation on Film]\n\n{{River item box\n|River      = [[River Tyne]]\n|upstream   = [[Swing Bridge, River Tyne|Swing Bridge]]\n|downstream = [[Gateshead Millennium Bridge]]\n|downsub    = [[Footbridge]]\n|location   = NZ253637}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1928]]\n[[Category:Transport in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Through arch bridges in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Crossings of the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed bridges]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:59c0:3be:c466:fca5:8271:461e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tyne_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Juan Cabral (director)", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine writer and director|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Juan Cabral''' (born, 1978) is an Argentine writer and director, whose work includes short and feature films, music videos and commercials.\n\n==Career==\nCabral wrote and directed [[Gorilla (advertisement)|''Gorilla'']] for [[Cadbury]] - voted 'Favourite Ad of all time'<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/224737/cadbury-s-gorilla-crowned-uk-s-favourite|title=Cadbury\u2019s gorilla crowned UK\u2019s favourite|last=Hancock|first=Edith|date=2015-09-21|website=www.cityam.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/cadburys-gorilla-nations-favourite-ad-industry-opts-guinness-surfer/1364711|title=Cadbury's Gorilla is nation's favourite ad, while industry opts for Guinness' Surfer|website=www.campaignlive.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media-network/2016/jan/07/how-we-made-cadburys-gorilla-ad|title='I was basically told: you are never showing this' \u2013 how we made Cadbury's Gorilla ad|last=Caird|first=Jo|date=2016-01-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> in the UK. He is also the creator of the famous Sony Bravia Trilogy ( ''Balls'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dandad.org/en/d-ad-sony-balls-case-study-insights/|title=Case Study: Sony Balls|website=D&AD|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> ''Paint'' and ''Playdoh'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/how-sony-got-its-bounce-back-6097090.html|title=How Sony got its bounce back|date=2006-06-26|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> Cabral has been written about in the Wall Street Journal, The Independent, The Guardian,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jul/14/mediatop100200877|title=81. Juan Cabral|date=2008-07-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Times and Esquire magazine and was also included in The Evening Standard 'London's most influential people' list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/television-and-radio-7282474.html|title=Television and Radio|date=2008-10-02|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\nCabral has won every major award in advertising<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.davidreviews.tv/Profiles/JuanCabral|title=Juan Cabral|website=www.davidreviews.tv|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/theoneshow/-award/5814/tate-tracks|title=TATE MODERN / TATE TRACKS|website=www.oneclub.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> (including over 25 Cannes Lions and two Cannes grand Prix<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jun/23/advertising|title=Cannes International Advertising Festival: Gorilla takes the top award|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2008-06-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>). His breathtaking advert for Ikea - ''Beds'' - was awarded Best Crafted Commercial of the year by BTAA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soundtreemusic.com/blog/ikea-beds-last-nights-btaa-awards|title=IKEA 'Beds' at last nights BTAA Awards :: soundtree|website=www.soundtreemusic.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> and also voted Best Campaign of the year by Campaign Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/campaign-juan-cabrals-best-work/1496875|title=My campaign: Juan Cabral's best work|website=www.campaignlive.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> In 2016 Cabral was nominated by the DGA for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Commercials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2016/160113-68th-Annual-DGA-Awards-Television-Commercial-and-Documentary-Nominees-Announced.aspx|title=DGA Announces Nominees for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Television, Commercials and Documentary for 2015 -|website=www.dga.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> He recently directed the Rolex 2019 Oscars campaign<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shootonline.com/video/rolex-goes-oscars-scorsese-inarritu-bigelow-cameron|title=Rolex Goes To Oscars With Scorsese, Inarritu, Bigelow, Cameron|website=SHOOTonline|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> featuring [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Alejandro Gonzalez I\u00f1arritu]], [[Kathryn Bigelow]] and [[James Cameron]].\n\nHis first feature film ''[[imdbtitle:3842684|Two/One]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/dominique-mcelligott-beau-bridges-boyd-holbrook-two-one-1202621139/|title=Film News Roundup: Dominique McElligott, Beau Bridges Join Boyd Holbrook\u2019s \u2018Two/One\u2019|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=2017-11-22|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/-boyd-holbrook-to-star-in-juan-cabrals-two/one/5117728.article|title=Boyd Holbrook to star in Juan Cabral\u2019s 'Two/One'|last=Wyche|first=Elbert|website=Screen|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> is premiering in the 2019 Tribeca Film Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/filmguide/two-one-2019|title=Two/One {{!}} 2019 Tribeca Film Festival|website=Tribeca|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> It stars [[Boyd Holbrook]] and [[imdbname:4664205|Song Yang]] and it's the story of two men who dream each other and are, in some strange way, the same person.\n\nCabral is developing other feature films, scripts and TV shows and is represented by the commercial production company, [http://www.mjz.com MJZ].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mjz.com/directors/juan-cabral/director/|title=Director|website=MJZ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6609156|Juan Cabral}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cabral, Juan}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine writer and director|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Juan Cabral''' (born, 1978) is an Argentine writer and director, whose work includes short and feature films, music videos and commercials.\n\n==Career==\nCabral wrote and directed [[Gorilla (advertisement)|''Gorilla'']] for Cadbury - voted 'Favourite Ad of all time'<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/224737/cadbury-s-gorilla-crowned-uk-s-favourite|title=Cadbury\u2019s gorilla crowned UK\u2019s favourite|last=Hancock|first=Edith|date=2015-09-21|website=www.cityam.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/cadburys-gorilla-nations-favourite-ad-industry-opts-guinness-surfer/1364711|title=Cadbury's Gorilla is nation's favourite ad, while industry opts for Guinness' Surfer|website=www.campaignlive.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media-network/2016/jan/07/how-we-made-cadburys-gorilla-ad|title='I was basically told: you are never showing this' \u2013 how we made Cadbury's Gorilla ad|last=Caird|first=Jo|date=2016-01-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> in the UK. He is also the creator of the famous Sony Bravia Trilogy ( ''Balls'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dandad.org/en/d-ad-sony-balls-case-study-insights/|title=Case Study: Sony Balls|website=D&AD|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> ''Paint'' and ''Playdoh'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/how-sony-got-its-bounce-back-6097090.html|title=How Sony got its bounce back|date=2006-06-26|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> Cabral has been written about in the Wall Street Journal, The Independent, The Guardian,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jul/14/mediatop100200877|title=81. Juan Cabral|date=2008-07-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Times and Esquire magazine and was also included in The Evening Standard 'London's most influential people' list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/television-and-radio-7282474.html|title=Television and Radio|date=2008-10-02|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\nCabral has won every major award in advertising<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.davidreviews.tv/Profiles/JuanCabral|title=Juan Cabral|website=www.davidreviews.tv|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/theoneshow/-award/5814/tate-tracks|title=TATE MODERN / TATE TRACKS|website=www.oneclub.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> (including over 25 Cannes Lions and two Cannes grand Prix<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jun/23/advertising|title=Cannes International Advertising Festival: Gorilla takes the top award|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2008-06-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>). His breathtaking advert for Ikea - ''Beds'' - was awarded Best Crafted Commercial of the year by BTAA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soundtreemusic.com/blog/ikea-beds-last-nights-btaa-awards|title=IKEA 'Beds' at last nights BTAA Awards :: soundtree|website=www.soundtreemusic.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> and also voted Best Campaign of the year by Campaign Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/campaign-juan-cabrals-best-work/1496875|title=My campaign: Juan Cabral's best work|website=www.campaignlive.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> In 2016 Cabral was nominated by the DGA for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Commercials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2016/160113-68th-Annual-DGA-Awards-Television-Commercial-and-Documentary-Nominees-Announced.aspx|title=DGA Announces Nominees for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Television, Commercials and Documentary for 2015 -|website=www.dga.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> He recently directed the Rolex 2019 Oscars campaign<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shootonline.com/video/rolex-goes-oscars-scorsese-inarritu-bigelow-cameron|title=Rolex Goes To Oscars With Scorsese, Inarritu, Bigelow, Cameron|website=SHOOTonline|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> featuring [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Alejandro Gonzalez I\u00f1arritu]], [[Kathryn Bigelow]] and [[James Cameron]].\n\nHis first feature film ''[[imdbtitle:3842684|Two/One]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/dominique-mcelligott-beau-bridges-boyd-holbrook-two-one-1202621139/|title=Film News Roundup: Dominique McElligott, Beau Bridges Join Boyd Holbrook\u2019s \u2018Two/One\u2019|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=2017-11-22|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/-boyd-holbrook-to-star-in-juan-cabrals-two/one/5117728.article|title=Boyd Holbrook to star in Juan Cabral\u2019s 'Two/One'|last=Wyche|first=Elbert|website=Screen|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> is premiering in the 2019 Tribeca Film Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/filmguide/two-one-2019|title=Two/One {{!}} 2019 Tribeca Film Festival|website=Tribeca|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> It stars [[Boyd Holbrook]] and [[imdbname:4664205|Song Yang]] and it's the story of two men who dream each other and are, in some strange way, the same person.\n\nCabral is developing other feature films, scripts and TV shows and is represented by the commercial production company, [http://www.mjz.com MJZ].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mjz.com/directors/juan-cabral/director/|title=Director|website=MJZ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6609156|Juan Cabral}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cabral, Juan}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine film directo